<title>
Targeting Beta amyloid: a clinical review of immunotherapeutic approaches in Alzheimer's disease.
</title>

<text>

<abstract>
As the societal and economic burdens of Alzheimer's disease (AD) continue to mount, so does the need for therapies that slow the progression of the illness. Beta amyloid has long been recognized as the pathologic hallmark of AD, and the past decade has seen significant progress in the development of various immunotherapeutic approaches targeting beta amyloid. This paper reviews active and passive approaches aimed at beta amyloid, with a focus on clinical trial data.
</abstract>

<sections.0>
1. ntroduction
lzheimer's disease () is by far the most common form of dementia, and the social and economic burdens of  continue to mount. n 2010, an estimated 36 million people worldwide were living with dementiaβ€”a number that is projected to increase to 66 million in 2030, and 115 million in 2050 [1]. ccording to the orld lzheimer eport, the worldwide cost of dementia is estimated at  $604 billion for 2010 [1], and according to one model, this cost has increased by 34% between 2005 and 2009 [2]. hese statistics must be considered in parallel with the immeasurable emotional and psychological burdens that  places on patients and families.
 ignificant progress in the treatment of  has been made since the initial description of the disease by lois lzheimer in 1907 [3]. holinesterase inhibitors and memantine are potential therapies for the management of many cognitive symptoms of , but these neurotransmitter-based approaches do not address the underlying pathology of the illness, and ultimately fail to prevent its progression. he pathologic triad of β€”the accumulation of toxic beta amyloid with the formation of extracellular beta-amyloid-containing plaques, the development of intracellular neurofibrillary tangles, and the degeneration of cerebral neuronsβ€”provides numerous potential targets for disease-modifying therapies. ultiple lines of evidence now suggest, however, that it is the production and/or deposition of toxic forms of beta amyloid, along with the slowing of beta-amyloid clearance, that act as the central and primary events in  pathogenesis, while neurofibrillary tangle formation and neuronal cell death occur downstream in this amyloid cascade [4β€“6]. ecent in vitro work has demonstrated that beta-amyloid dimers (the major form of soluble oligomers in the human brain) isolated from patients with  induce both the abnormal phosphorylation of tau that is characteristic of  and the degeneration of neurites, providing further confirmation of the pivotal role of beta amyloid in the pathogenesis of  [7]. he search for a disease modifying therapyβ€”one that affects underlying pathology and has a measurable and long-lasting effect on the progression of disabilityβ€”has thus been aimed primarily at the study of beta amyloid.
 he demonstration of disease modification is best supported by both clinical and biomarker endpoints.  biomarker is an objectively measured characteristic that can be evaluated as an indicator of normal biologic processes, pathogenic processes, or pharmacologic responses to a therapeutic intervention [8]. everal potential biomarkers have been identified in  and are currently under investigation in interventional clinical trials. hese biomarkers should be reflective of changes in the pathology of the  brain, such as cerebral beta-amyloid deposition, abnormal phosphorylation of tau, or neurodegeneration.
 ecent advances in positron emission tomography () imaging have made possible the in vivo detection and quantification of beta amyloid using amyloid-specific ligands, such as the 11 ittsburgh ompound  (i. B) [9, 10]. Elevated levels of tau protein in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) are markers of active neuronal degeneration [11], while levels of abnormally phosphorylated tau (P-tau) appear to correlate with the quantity of neurofibrillary tangles in the brain, suggesting that CSF P-tau may serve as an in vivo biomarker of the neurofibrillary pathology of AD [12]. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)- based measures of cerebral atrophy, most likely the result of excessive neuronal death, correlate closely with the rate of neuropsychological decline in patients with AD [13]. These and other biomarkers will likely play an important role in demonstrating the effect of any therapy on cerebral amyloid and the downstream processes that are affected through beta-amyloid removal.
